How would you provision and onboard multiple AWS accounts using Terraform and AWS Organizations?

In UI

Yes, invite (Organizations console → Add account → Invite existing), accept (from the target account), and move to OU (Actions → Move) are all doable via UI. Guardrails auto-apply once moved into the OU; deeper security retrofitting (CloudTrail/Config/SSO) still needs manual steps whether via UI or CLI.

1. Invite the existing account (from Management account)

- Go to AWS Organizations console → AWS accounts
- Click Add an AWS account → Select Invite an existing AWS account
- Enter the account ID or email of the existing account
- Optionally add a note
- Click Send invitation

This is the UI equivalent of:
invite-account-to-organization

2. Accept the invitation (from the existing/standalone account)

- Log into the existing account (the one being invited)
- Go to AWS Organizations console
- You'll see a pending invitation on the dashboard
- Click Accept

Note:
You need to log in as that account—the accept step can't be done from the management account.

3. Move the account into the correct OU

• Back in the management account, go to AWS Organizations → AWS accounts
• The newly joined account will appear under the Root by default
• Select the account → click Actions → Move
• Choose the destination OU (e.g., "Prod OU")
• Click Move

This is the UI equivalent of `move-account`.

4. Guardrails/SCPs — automatic once moved

• Once moved into that OU, it automatically inherits whatever SCPs are attached to that OU — no separate UI step needed for this part; it's structural (same as new accounts)
• You can verify by going to Policies → Service control policies, and checking which policies show as attached to that OU

------
In CLI
------

1. Send an invitation from the management account:

aws organizations invite-account-to-organization \
  --target Id=123456789012,Type=ACCOUNT \
  --notes "Join company Org"

2. Accept the invitation — from within the existing/standalone account:

aws organizations accept-handshake --handshake-id <handshake-id>

3. Move it into the correct OU (it lands in the root by default after joining):

aws organizations move-account \
  --account-id 123456789012 \
  --source-parent-id <root-id> \
  --destination-parent-id <target-ou-id>

4. Now it inherits SCPs/guardrails from that OU — same as a freshly-created account would.

What is AWS Organizations?

AWS Organizations is a service to centrally manage multiple AWS accounts under one root. It provides consolidated billing, 
SCPs to enforce policies across all accounts, and OUs to group accounts by environment or department.

It is a service that helps you manage multiple AWS accounts centrally from one place.

Simple Analogy

Without AWS Organizations:
Each AWS account is separate
Different billing, different policies
You login to each account separately
→ hard to manage

With AWS Organizations:
All accounts under ONE umbrella
Single billing, central policies
Manage all from one place
→ like a company with departments

Structure

Root (Top Level)
      │
      ├── Management Account (Master)
      │         └── pays all bills
      │
      ├── OU (Organizational Unit)
      │     ├── Dev Account
      │     └── Test Account
      │
      ├── OU Production
      │     ├── Prod Account
      │     └── DR Account
      │
      └── OU Security
            ├── Log Archive Account
            └── Audit Account

| Feature              | What it does                             |
| -------------------- | ---------------------------------------- |
| Consolidated Billing | Single bill for all accounts             |
| SCPs                 | Apply policies across all accounts       |
| OUs                  | Group accounts by department/environment |
| Account Factory      | Create new accounts automatically        |


SCP — Service Control Policy

Management Account applies SCP
          │
          ▼
    All child accounts
    automatically follow

Example SCP:
"No one can disable CloudTrail"
→ applies to Dev, Staging, Prod
→ even account root user cannot bypass
---------
Consolidated Billing Benefit

Without Organizations:
  Dev Account     → separate bill
  Prod Account    → separate bill
  Security Account → separate bill

With Organizations:
  All accounts → ONE bill
                + volume discounts
                + easy cost tracking
---------
Control Tower vs Organizations

AWS Organizations    =  Foundation (the structure)
AWS Control Tower    =  Built on top of Organizations
                        (adds guardrails, automation,
                         dashboard, account factory)

Control Tower needs Organizations to work
Organizations can work without Control Tower
